{

  "response_text": "The mean green biomass initiates at 45,000 units and undergoes a marked decline during the first three decades, reaching a nadir of approximately 42,057 units at year 27. This initial deterioration reflects the impact of initial stocking densities (90 animals per household across 60 stationary farms) on vegetation resources before adaptive learning mechanisms effectively modulate grazing pressure.\n\nFollowing the minimum at year 27, biomass stabilizes briefly before commencing a sustained multidecadal recovery. From approximately year 33 through year 54, vegetation increases rapidly with acceleration peaking during years 44-54 at nearly 955 units per annum. This phase coincides with the effective implementation of experiential and social learning strategies, as farmers adjust stocking decisions based on observed pasture conditions and neighbor outcomes within the one-patch knowledge radius.\n\nAfter year 54, the rate of biomass accumulation gradually decelerates—dropping to roughly 379 units per year in years 55-65, then to approximately 55 units by years 66-76, and continuing to slow through the remainder of the simulation—yet maintains a consistent positive trajectory through year 98. \n\nThe simulation concludes at year 100 with biomass reaching 60,535 units, representing the maximum observed value and substantially exceeding initial conditions by approximately 34%. This long-term enhancement indicates that under the combined influence of learning-by-doing and social learning, the grazing system achieves a higher vegetation steady-state than its initial configuration, despite significant interannual rainfall variability (coefficient of variation of 50%). The inflection points at years 9 and 49 demarcate transitions between the degradation, stabilization, and recovery phases, with the change point at year 50 marking the shift from rapid rehabilitation to gradual maturation toward the elevated biomass equilibrium."
}

